      "content": "If the cargo is lost or stolen during transit under a CIF agreement, the claim filing is a bit of a tangled knot, but it usually starts with the party who holds the insurance policy. Since the seller in a CIF arrangement is contractually obligated to arrange and pay for the insurance, they are generally the ones who initiate the claim with the insurance company.\n\nThe seller has the policy, so they are the primary contact for filing the claim. They are the ones who have the documentation—the bill of lading, the commercial invoice, and the insurance certificate—that proves the goods were covered.\n\nHowever, the ultimate financial responsibility for the loss falls back to the buyer, because the buyer is the one who ultimately owns the goods and is the one who needs the goods to complete their transaction. It's a classic tug-of-war, though the seller is usually the one doing the heavy lifting with the paperwork.\n\nIt reminds me of when I tried to organize a shipment of particularly stubborn, oversized garden gnomes. The paperwork was a nightmare! You need to make sure every little piece is accounted for, or you'll end up with a whole pile of misplaced ceramic heads, just like a disorganized shipment. Don't let the",
